Prove that all numbers are represented in binary, let $n=\left(\overline{a_{m} a_{m-1} \cdots a_{1} a_{0}}\right)_{2}$. We will use mathematical induction to prove: $x_{n}=\left(\overline{b_{m} b_{m-1} \cdots b_{1} b_{0}}\right)_{2}$, where $b_{m}=a_{m}=1, b_{i} \equiv a_{i}+a_{i+1}(\bmod 2), i=0,1,2, \cdots, m-1$.

When $n=1$, the proposition is obviously true. Assume the proposition holds for natural numbers less than $n$. For $n=\left(\overline{a_{m} \cdots a_{1} a_{0}}\right)_{2}$, let $n^{\prime}=\left(\overline{a_{m} \cdots a_{1}}\right)_{2}$, by the hypothesis:
(1) If $a_{1} a_{0}=00$, then $x_{n}=2 x_{n^{\prime}}=2 \cdot\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1}}\right)_{2}=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} b_{0}}\right)_{2}$;
(2) If $a_{1} a_{0}=10$, then $x_{n}=2 x_{n^{\prime}}+1=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} 1}\right)_{2}=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} b_{0}}\right)_{2}$;
(3) If $a_{1} a_{0}=01$, then $x_{n}=2 x_{n^{n}}+1=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} 1}\right)_{2}=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} b_{0}}\right)_{2}$;
(4) If $a_{1} a_{0}=11$, then $x_{n}=2 x_{n^{\prime}}=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} 0}\right)_{2}=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} b_{0}}\right)_{2}$.
Thus, the proposition holds for $n$ as well.
If $x_{n}=\left(\overline{b_{m} \cdots b_{1} b_{0}}\right)_{2}$, then for any number $\left(\overline{b_{m} b_{m-1} \cdots b_{1} b_{0}}\right)_{2}$, we can uniquely determine $n=\left(\overline{a_{m} a_{m-1} \cdots a_{1} a_{0}}\right)_{2}$ as follows:
$$
a_{m}=b_{m}=1 \text{, and } a_{i} \equiv b_{i}-a_{i+1}(\bmod 2) \text{. }
$$

Therefore, $n \rightarrow x_{n}$ is a one-to-one correspondence from $N \rightarrow N$, and the proposition is proved.

